A. Pagaltzis wrote:
&gt; * John Panzer &lt;jpanzer@...&gt; [2007-06-28 18:25]:
&gt;   
&gt;&gt; There was also an assumption in the W3 WG that they were
&gt;&gt; talking about byte range updates, and I think that what we
&gt;&gt; really are looking at is infoset level deltas. Which I think
&gt;&gt; changes the discussion.
&gt;&gt;     
&gt;
&gt; Exactly. The applicability of PUT with Content-Range is quite
&gt; limited: you can only modify a single contiguous region of the
&gt; resource per request, and it requires that the server support
&gt; octet-level addressing on the underlying resource in the first
&gt; place. Supporting Content-Range on GET is easy, even if the data
&gt; is plucked from a database and then rendered through a template;
&gt; supporting Content-Range on PUT in this scenario is… very tricky,
&gt; to say the least.
&gt;
&gt; And of course, there’s the gnarly problem of Content-Range
&gt; getting dropped in some scenarios.
&gt;
&gt; PATCH, OTOH, has none of these issues. You can modify as many
&gt; parts of the resource at once as you want, expressing
&gt; modifications at an arbitrary level of abstraction, and failure
&gt; in transit is more reliable.
&gt;
&gt;   
Both Content-Range and PATCH need to define infoset-level extensions.  
Content-Range might possibly be dropped silently by very broken 
intermediaries, but PATCH is known to be blocked by some proxies in 
certain configurations (e.g., Squid).  I don&#39;t see a clear winner.
&gt; Regards,
&gt;   


